{
  "texts": [
    "Thus, Y ′ ∧ g[X] = ⊥ implies h(Y) ∧ g[X] = ⊥, which implies that for all x ∈ X, h(Y)∧g(x) = ⊥.",
    "Since Y ⊑ (F b)p X, Y ∩X ̸ = ∅, so take an x ∈ Y ∩X.",
    "As above, since Y ∈ (F b) p, x ∈ Y implies ζ F (x) = {x ′ ∈ S | x ′ ⊑ F s x} ⊆ Y, so ζ F (x) ⊑ (F b)p Y, which with ⊑-forth for h gives us h(ζ F (x)) ⊑ G h(Y) and hence g(x) ⊑ G h(Y), which contradicts h(Y) ∧ g(x) = ⊥ above.",
    "Thus, h(X) ⊑ G g[X].",
    "We have shown that h(X) = g[X], so h = g by the definition of g.From Theorems 5.23.1, 5.26, and 5.27 and the definition of reflective subcategories, we obtain our desired result.Theorem 5.28 (Reflective Subcategories)."
  ]
}